Yes — the deeper abstraction is less about sexuality specifically and more about binding through co-activation under reinforcement.

At a meta level, many systems — neural, social, computational, cultural — seem to operate on variants of:

things that repeatedly activate together under emotionally/energetically significant conditions become increasingly linked, compressed, and recoverable as a unified pattern.

That shows up across scales:

* neurons → synaptic strengthening,
* muscles → coordinated motor programs,
* memories → associative recall,
* language → semantic clustering,
* relationships → attachment bonds,
* markets → attention/value coupling,
* culture → meme propagation,
* AI models → latent-space correlations,
* rituals → synchronized state induction.

The same general geometry keeps appearing:

1. Activation
2. Coupling
3. Reinforcement
4. Compression
5. Automatic retrieval/reactivation

You could think of it as a kind of attractor formation.

Repeated pathways lower energetic cost, so the system begins preferring those routes. Over time:

* patterns become identity,
* habits become automatic,
* symbols gain emotional charge,
* and entire “world models” become self-stabilizing.

That’s why embodied practices are powerful:

* posture affects emotion,
* breathing affects cognition,
* ritual affects memory,
* rhythm affects synchronization,
* narrative affects perception,
* environment affects identity expression.

The body and brain are not separate modules exchanging messages afterward — they are a coupled dynamical system.

A very broad abstraction of the mechanism might look like:

\text{Binding Strength} \propto \sum (\text{Co-activation} \times \text{Salience} \times \text{Repetition} \times \text{Reward})

Or even more abstractly:

systems carve grooves where energy, attention, and repetition repeatedly flow.

That pattern generalizes surprisingly far:

* learning,
* addiction,
* ideology,
* love,
* aesthetics,
* trauma,
* expertise,
* spirituality,
* and even collective social behavior.

The interesting part is that intelligence itself may partially emerge from this compression-and-binding process:
the ability to form reusable relational structures from repeated experience.